{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472037"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:54:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:54:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"938"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/938"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.05,0.04,0.57,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"938"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57167"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/938"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"938"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42626"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"549"},{"type":"tags","id":"2163"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"274"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10669"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10872"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17231"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57167"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of a painless swelling in her neck. The swelling is slowly increasing in size. She has not noticed any voice changes, nor has she experienced any difficulty in swallowing or breathing. She is otherwise in good health. On examination, there is a soft, smooth-surfaced 3 cm diameter swelling in the anterior midline of the neck. The swelling is not attached to the overlying skin and moves on swallowing and on protrusion of the tongue.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely origin of her current problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abnormal growth of first to fourth pharyngeal pouches","Diverticular growth from the embryological pharynx","Abnormal growth of sublingual folds","Remnants of a structure from foetal development","Benign growth of the thyroid gland"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is the characteristic description of a thyroglossal cyst - the age of the patient, its anatomical position, the rapid increase in size, and elevation when the tongue is protruded. This differentiates it from a goitre, which is a benign growth of the thyroid gland that does not rise when the tongue is protruded. A thyroglossal cyst can form at any site along the tract of the \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroglossal duct\u003C/strong\u003E, which extends from the foramen caecum in the base of the tongue to the thyroid\u2019s location in the neck. Failure of closure of the duct can lead to cyst formation after descent of the thyroid gland. The thyroglossal duct will usually involute by the tenth week of gestation. Some 7% of the population will have some sort of thyroid gland developmental abnormality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAbnormal growth from the first through fourth pharyngeal pouches indicates a branchial cyst and would be more lateral, as it is attached to the anterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle. Thyroid lesions are diverticular growths from the embryological pharynx and would not move upwards on protrusion of the tongue. Abnormal growths of sublingual folds on the floor of the mouth describe a sublingual adenoma and would be very unusual in a patient of this age, and such lesions would more likely be found immediately under the jaw and more lateral to the swelling described.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thyroglossal cysts are the most common congenital abnormalities of the neck.","A midline swelling in the neck of young individuals is most likely to be a thyroglossal cyst."],"references":["Patel S, Bhatt AA. Thyroglossal duct pathology and mimics. Insights into Imaging 2019; 10:12. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30725193/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42626"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"938"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14566"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14566"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d489ff4f-a8eb-4361-bbb5-819dde39b385.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d489ff4f-a8eb-4361-bbb5-819dde39b385.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":314,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42626"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-24T22:24:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-24T22:25:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"938"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57167"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[]